^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me discuss the auction first. Some people felt that Ruth was not strong enough to reverse. I think she was strong enough for sure. Yes, she only has 14 HCP but as people say, her hand is much better than that. She can add 2 length points for the hearts, and 2 points for the quality suits giving her 18 Bergen Starting points. |
PG| ***** 100 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For those who like Losing Trick Count, her hand is a 5 loser hand, also worth a reverse. However, I think 3@H is a better bid. Granted, I might not bid 3N over 3@H if I have enough points but lack a spade stopper. Also as you know in 2/1 we need to mind two situations.|
PG| ***** 101 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Situation A - if the auction goes 1@H-2 minor-2@S, 2@S is technically a reverse. However, because 2 minor is a game force, many (probably a majority of) experts play that 2@S does not show extra values. It is merely bidding out your shape and can be done with a min opener.|
PG| ***** 102 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Situation B - if the auction goes 1@H-1N-2@S, that is definitely a reverse. 1N is not a game force and can, in fact, be done with a weak hand. So opener should not bypass 2@H unless they have a nice hand. Situation B is what we have here.|
PG| ***** 103 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at| 3@H, however, is more precise, showing 6 nice hearts and her medium strength opener (not game forcing). There is also some question as to whether my 2N was forcing. I play, as I mentioned during last session, 2N would not be forcing. Therefore, I should have bid 3@C, a forcing bid, because with 10 HCP I want to be in game over against a reverse hand. Regardless, we ended up in the best contract.|
PG| ***** 104 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play, my two comments are Jacquie's play of the @DA, trick 6, when Ruth played a diamond. She violated my 2nd hand low rule. In her defense, some of you may say, well if she didn't play the @DA and Ruth decided to play the king, she loses a diamond trick. That is maybe true as far as it goes. However even if Ruth plays the @DK all Jacquie is doing is trading tricks. |
PG| ***** 105 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Because then Ruth does not get a discard on the @DK. So, almost always, 2nd hand low, especially when you hold the Ace and the King-Jack is in dummy. Ruth might very well have decided to play the Jack. Then her side would certainly had 2 diamond tricks. I know its hard, but if you always play 2nd hand low, I promise you you will come out ahead in the long run. At trick 3, Liza also violated the 2nd hand low rule in spades, and ended setting up Ruth's @S7. Trust me on 2nd hand low :).|
